name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
We must channel our collective outrage into change. We cannot end violence with more violence. 

Our country is crying out for change -- and that change requires all of us to make it happen. 

10/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
I condemn the violence which has inflicted further trauma on a community already reeling from tragedy, the moral and social upheaval from generations of systemic racism, the killings of unarmed black men and women and the economic and health toll of the covid pandemic.

9/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
You have my word that I will fight like hell to get this bill passed. 

I strongly support the Wallace family‚Äôs call for peace and civil discourse in the wake of this tragedy. 

8/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
Just last week, I joined @RepPressley, @RepKatiePorter, @RepCardenas in introducing a bill that would provide grants and training to help cities to have mental health professionals available to respond to 911 calls for people in mental health crisis. 

7/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
At the community meeting, we learned that Philly recently started a project to include mental health professionals in the 911 response center, but due to staffing/funding limitations, the mental health professional wasn‚Äôt on duty when the Wallace family called for help. 

6/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
We have a long road ahead of us to repair the trust and faith lost between our police and the communities they serve. 

The culture of policing must change and policing of mental illness must end. 

5/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
But, we don‚Äôt need to wait for an investigation to tell us that the Wallace family‚Äôs call for help should have been answered by mental health professionals not police.

As a society, we have failed Black people. As a society, we have failed people with mental illness. 

4/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
The Police Commissioner and District Attorney have pledged to conduct thorough investigations and deliver justice for Mr. Wallace and his family.

3/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
27 year old Walter Wallace Jr. should be alive right now. My heart is with his family, this community, and everyone who has been traumatized by his death.

2/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
Last night, I attended a community meeting in West Philadelphia organized by local officials and members of the Black Clergy. We heard from community leaders and neighbors grieving a tragedy that should have never happened.

1/10

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message: In addition to this mom being separated from her daughters, we saw dozens of women and children in holding cells, sleeping side by side on benches and cement floors with no room to walk between their bodies, no windows, and no place for the children to play.

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
Her older daughter was withdrawn, and we learned that she was having difficulty with the reunion. 

It was easy to see how conflicted the little girl was and her struggle to reconcile the attachment she had formed to her foster family.

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
This mom described how much of a toll being separated from her little girls had on her, but she didn‚Äôt have to. 

We could see it in her face, in her tears, and in the way she and her younger daughter clung to each other.

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
She walked across the border with her daughters and requested asylum.  Her daughters were taken from her and placed in foster care.

No reason was given for this separation.

name: Scanlon, Mary-Gay
message:
I feel the need to share this story with you all again tonight. 

When I went to our southern border last February, I met with a mother who was just reunited with her children the night before. 

(Thread)
